JOHANNESBURG – The United Kingdom has invested over $100-million in the Zimbabwean economy. This is the largest investment on the UK-Zim relationship since London imposed sanctions on Robert Mugabe’s regime in the early 2000s. READ: 'Massive response' to Zim's calls for investment, relocation of exiled citizens It is also the first direct commercial loan to the southern African nation’s private sector in more than 20 years. Britain’s development finance institution, CDC, said the government is well aware of the risks associated with the economy. READ: EU ready to support Zimbabwe engage foreign lenders But it said it will share the default risk on loans, to provide foreign exchange to dollar-starved Zimbabwean businesses that are struggling to operate. eNCA